{
  "masechta": "Gittin",
  "daf": 8,
  "amud": "a-b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Definition of Eretz Yisrael for Gittin: Boats in Rivers vs. Mediterranean Waters",
      "display_title": "Eretz Yisrael Borders",
      "timestamp": "00:29",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The debate between Rabbi Yehuda and Chachamim regarding boats with soil in rivers of Eretz Yisrael and the comparison to a planter with a hole",
          "display_title": "Boat/Planter Debate",
          "timestamp": "00:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's explanation: formal definitions from Terumot u'Ma'asrot are applied to Gittin purposes despite practical concerns about lishma and validation of signatures",
          "display_title": "Tosafot: Formal Definiti…",
          "timestamp": "02:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Nachman's position: nobody disputes that rivers in Eretz Yisrael are within the borders; the debate concerns the Mediterranean Sea",
          "display_title": "Rav Nachman: Rivers",
          "timestamp": "08:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "The teaching regarding the definition of Eretz Yisrael and Chutz La'aretz for Terumot purposes: the line from Turei Amnon to Nachal Mitzrayim",
          "display_title": "Turei Amnon Border",
          "timestamp": "10:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Islands in the Mediterranean: Tanna Kamma draws a line connecting northern and southern borders; Rabbi Yehuda extends it to include more Mediterranean waters as Israel",
          "display_title": "Island Definition",
          "timestamp": "12:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's discussion: whether distant lands like France/Spain would fall under Rabbi Yehuda's expanded definition; three possible answers addressing practical concerns",
          "display_title": "Tosafot: France Question",
          "timestamp": "19:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Three Distinct Definitions of Eretz Yisrael: Terumot u'Ma'asrot, Gittin, and Slavery Laws",
      "display_title": "Three Definitions",
      "timestamp": "24:32",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Meir's ruling: Akko counts as Eretz Yisrael for Gittin purposes only",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Meir: Akko",
          "timestamp": "24:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "The question of selling a slave to Syria (Surya): whether it counts as selling to Chutz La'aretz",
          "display_title": "Slave to Syria",
          "timestamp": "24:49"
        },
        {
          "title": "The distinction: Akko is like Eretz Yisrael for Gittin but like Chutz La'aretz for slave laws, showing graduated definitions",
          "display_title": "Graduated Definitions",
          "timestamp": "26:25"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Syria (Surya): Three Ways Similar to Eretz Yisrael and Three Ways Similar to Chutz La'aretz",
      "display_title": "Syria's Status",
      "timestamp": "32:26",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Teachings regarding Syria's status in three ways: the dirt is tamei (tumah), selling a slave there is like selling to Chutz La'aretz, and bringing a get from there requires bifnei nechtam",
          "display_title": "Syria: Three Chutz",
          "timestamp": "32:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Syria is obligated in Ma'aser and Shvi'it like Eretz Yisrael due to the concept of Kibush Yachid (individual conquest by King David)",
          "display_title": "Kibush Yachid",
          "timestamp": "34:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rashi's explanation of Kibush Yachid: David's conquest was not a national enterprise with all Israel participating or Sanhedrin approval",
          "display_title": "Rashi: Kibush Yachid",
          "timestamp": "35:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's alternative explanation of Kibush Yachid: land conquered before the primary land of Israel was fully conquered cannot be annexed for kedusha purposes",
          "display_title": "Tosafot: Kibush Yachid",
          "timestamp": "37:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "One can enter Syria while maintaining tahara by avoiding direct contact with the soil; in other Chutz La'aretz, even the air is considered tamei",
          "display_title": "Tahara in Syria",
          "timestamp": "41:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Purchasing fields in Syria is encouraged as it is considered like purchasing in the center of Yerushalayim; one may have a non-Jew write the deed even on Shabbat for yishuv Eretz Yisrael",
          "display_title": "Purchasing Fields",
          "timestamp": "44:27"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Case of a Slave Bringing His Own Writ of Manumission: Validation of Signatures and Property Transfer",
      "display_title": "Slave's Get Shichrur",
      "timestamp": "49:46",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "A slave who brings his own writ of manumission stating he and all the master's property are given to him: he acquires freedom but not the property",
          "display_title": "Eved Brings Get",
          "timestamp": "49:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "The reason: bifnei nechtam works to validate the signature for the status change of manumission (get shichrur) but not for a gift document (matana)",
          "display_title": "Get vs. Gift",
          "timestamp": "50:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "The debate between Abaye and Rava: whether one sentence containing both elements can have bifnei nechtam apply to one element (freedom) but not another (property transfer)",
          "display_title": "Abaye vs. Rava",
          "timestamp": "52:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's position: regardless of whether the statement is one sentence or two, bifnei nechtam validates the freedom aspect but not the property aspect, splitting the legal effect",
          "display_title": "Rava's Position",
          "timestamp": "55:34"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
